It is funny, actually. Humor often feels spontaneous, but it’s remarkably rule-governed underneath.

A lot of jokes rely on the audience unconsciously predicting one trajectory, then the punchline forcing a rapid reinterpretation. Some common patterns are:

* Expectation → violation.
* Ambiguity → resolution.
* Escalation → release.
* Literal ↔ figurative flip.
* Status reversal.
* Taboo crossed in a way the audience perceives as safe or surprising.

Your example, “Yeah, I’m fucking him,” has that kind of trajectory-dependent quality. Whether it lands depends almost entirely on context. If the audience has been led to interpret “I’m with him” or “I’m supporting him,” then the sudden switch to a blunt sexual meaning creates an unexpected reinterpretation. If the context already points toward sex, it won’t have the same effect because there’s no surprise.

So in a way, comedy is less about random funny words than about steering the audience’s prediction engine. The comedian controls the trajectory of interpretation, then nudges it just enough that the audience suddenly has to update their mental model. That moment of rapid model revision is often what people experience as the laugh.